04622nam a22006015i 9780822397663DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223976637 a10.1515/97808223976632doi  a(DE-B1597)554148  a(OCoLC)1229161443  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS374.R32bM38 1999 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aMcKee, Patricia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProducing American Races :bHenry James, William Faulkner, Toni Morrison /cPatricia McKee. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Race and Media -- tChapter One. Reproducing Whiteness: The Wings of the Dove -- tChapter Two. Collective Whiteness in The Golden Bowl -- tChapter Three. Self-Division as Racial Divide: The Sound and the Fury -- tChapter Four. Playing White Men in Light in August -- tChapter Five. Black Spaces in Sula -- tChapter Six. Off the Record: Jazz and the Production of Black Culture -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Producing American Races Patricia McKee examines three authors who have powerfully influenced the formation of racial identities in the United States: Henry James, William Faulkner, and Toni Morrison. Using their work to argue that race becomes visible only through image production and exchange, McKee illuminates the significance that representational practice has had in the process of racial construction.McKee provides close readings of six novels-James's The Wings of the Dove and The Golden Bowl, Faulkner's The Sound and the Fury and Light in August, and Morrison's Sula and Jazz-interspersed with excursions into Lacanian and Freudian theory, critical race theory, epistemology, and theories of visuality. In James and Faulkner, she finds, race is represented visually through media that highlight ways of seeing and being seen. Written in the early twentieth century, the novels of James and Faulkner reveal how whiteness depended on visual culture even before film and television became its predominant media. In Morrison, the culture is aural and oral-and often about the absence of the visual. Because Morrison's African American communities produce identity in nonvisual, even anti-visual terms, McKee argues, they refute not just white representations of black persons as objects but also visual orders of representation that have constructed whites as subjects and blacks as objects.With a theoretical approach that both complements and transcends current scholarship about race-and especially whiteness-Producing American Races will engage scholars in American literature, critical race theory, African American studies, and cultural studies. It will also be of value to those interested in the novel as a political and aesthetic form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRace in literature. 0aWhites in literature. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397663zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397663.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  